String

1) Trimming

strip() # leading & tailing character remove by default space
lstrip() # Leading / left side character removed bydefault space
rstrip() # tailing / right side character removed bydefault space
# we have to specify character which we want to remove inside '' single quote

e.g 
text1 = '      hello     '
text2= '$$$$$$hello$$$$$'
print(text1.strip())
print(text2.strip('$'))
hello
hello



2) Splitting and Joining

split() # using this function we split the text into list
e.g
email='ro@gmail.com'
print(email.split('@'))
['ro', 'gmail.com']
e.g
products='milk,bread,jam'
print(products.split(','))
['milk', 'bread', 'jam']

join() # Joins element of an iterable with the string as a seprator
e.g
#simple concatenation
s1='python'
s2='session'
print(s1+s2)
'pythonsession'
e.g
#using join
print('-'.join([s1,s2]) )  #join takes only one argument so we provide as a list . here we join using -
'python-session'
e.g
'''The join() method in Python inserts the calling string (s1 = 'python') between each character of the given iterable 
(s2 = 'session').
So, 'python'.join('session') means that the string 'python' is inserted between each letter of 'session'.'''
print(s1.join(s2))
'spythonepythonspythonspythonipythonopythonn'



3) Formatting
formate = Formats the string using placeholder
f-strings(f"{var}" - faster and more redable string formatting
A format string is a string that includes placeholders to insert values dynamically — like variables, numbers, or other data — into the string.
e.g
name='Sanika'
age=23
course='DS'
print(f'{name} is {age} years old and takes {course} course and fee is {2333+1233}') #we also add mathematics here
Sanika is 23 years old and takes DS course and fee is 3566


